{{Infobox person | honorific_prefix = Chief | name = Kofoworola Abeni Pratt | honorific_suffix = Hon. FRCN | image = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = 1910 | birth_place = [[Nigeria]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1992|06|18|1910|df=y}} | death_place = | nationality = [[Nigerian people|Nigerian]] | other_names = | occupation = [[Nurse]] | known_for = }}
[[Chieftain|Chief]] '''Kofoworola Abeni Pratt''' [[Fellow of the Royal College of Nursing|Hon. FRCN]] (1910–1992) was a [[Nigeria]]n-born nurse who is regarded as the first [[black people|black]] nurse to work in Britain's [[National Health Service]].<ref name="tls">{{cite news|title=Wonderful adventures: How did Mary Seacole come to be viewed as a pioneer of modern nursing?|url=http://www.uoguelph.ca/~cwfn/short/tls-seacole.htm|accessdate=11 July 2016|work=Times Literary Supplement|date=6 December 2013|page=14-15}}</ref> She subsequently became vice-president of the [[International Council of Nurses]] and the first black [[Federal Ministry of Health (Nigeria)|Chief Nursing Officer]] of Nigeria, working in the [[Federal Ministry of Health (Nigeria)|Federal Ministry of Health]].<ref name="Bell">{{cite journal |title=Kofoworola Abeni Pratt; third vice-president, International Council of Nurses |last=Bell|first=L. M.|date=October 1967|journal=Int Nurs Rev.|volume=14|issue=5|pages=7–10|pmid=4864502}}</ref><ref name="WH">{{Cite episode |title=Listener Week |series=Woman's Hour |serieslink=Woman's Hour |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b07jqql8 |access-date=11 July 2016 |station=[[BBC Radio Four]] |date=11 July 2016 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= }}</ref>
Pratt, who was born to a prominent Nigerian family, studied to be a teacher at the [[United Missionary College]] in [[Ibadan]], after her father discouraged her from her wish to be a nurse.<ref name="Matera">{{cite book |url=https://rucore.libraries.rutgers.edu/rutgers-lib/24439/ |title=Black Internationalism and African and Caribbean Intellectuals in London 1919–1950 |last=Matera |first=Marc |date=May 2008 |doi=10.7282/T38S4Q7V |accessdate=11 July 2016}}</ref> From 1936 to 1940 she taught at a [[Church Missionary Society]] girls' school in Nigeria.<ref name="Matera" /> She subsequently married to an Englishman, Dr. E. S. O. Pratt,<ref name="Matera" /> and, after moving to England in 1946,<ref name="Matera" /> studied nursing at the [[Florence Nightingale Faculty of Nursing and Midwifery|Nightingale School]] at [[St Thomas' Hospital]], in London,<ref name="tls" /><ref name="WH" /> qualifying as a [[State Registered Nurse]] in 1950.<ref name="Matera" /> It was unusual for a married woman to be allowed to take up nursing at that time.<ref name="WH" /> During her time in London, she was active in the [[West African Students' Union]],<ref name="Matera" /> an association of students from various West African countries who were studying in the United Kingdom, and which, in 1942, had called for the independence of Britain's West African colonies.<ref name="Adi">Hakim Adi, ''West Africans in Britain 1900–1960: Nationalism, Pan-Africanism and Communism'', London: Lawrence & Wishart, 1998. {{ISBN|978-0853158486}}.</ref> Pratt returned to Nigeria in 1954. She was appointed [[Matron]] of the [[University College Hospital, Ibadan|University College Hospital]] in Ibadan within ten years, being the first Nigerian to hold that position.<ref name="Matera" /> She was [[Commissioner of Health]] for [[Lagos]] in the 1970s.<ref name="Litcaf">{{cite web|url=http://litcaf.com/kofoworola-abeni-pratt/|title=Kofoworola Abeni Pratt|work=[[Litcaf]]|accessdate=11 July 2016}}</ref>
In 1973 she was awarded the [[Florence Nightingale Medal]] by the [[International Committee of the Red Cross]]. The citation described her as a:<ref name="ICRC-73">{{cite journal|title=Twenty-fourth award of the Florence Nightingale Medal |journal=International Review of the Red Cross |date=May 1973 |issue=146 |page=242 |url=https://www.loc.gov/rr/frd/Military_Law/pdf/RC_May-1973.pdf |accessdate=11 July 2016}}</ref>
{{Quote|State Registered Nurse and Midwife. Certificate in Tropical Nursing. Teachers Diploma. Hospital Nursing Administration Certificate. Chief Nursing Officer, Federal Ministry of Health, Lagos.}} The award was presented to her by the President of the [[Nigerian Red Cross Society]], Sir [[Adetokunbo Ademola]], on 21 December 1973.<ref name="ICRC-74">{{cite journal|title=Twenty-fourth award of the Florence Nightingale Medal |journal=International Review of the Red Cross |date=May 1974 |issue=147 |page=250 |url=https://www.loc.gov/rr/frd/Military_Law/pdf/RC_May-1974.pdf |accessdate=11 July 2016}}</ref> In 1979 she was made an honorary fellow of the [[Royal College of Nursing]].<ref>{{cite web|title=RCN Fellowship and Honorary Fellowship Roll of Honour|url=http://rcn.funnelback.co.uk/search/click.cgi?rank=1&collection=rcn-meta&url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.rcn.org.uk%2F-%2Fmedia%2Froyal-college-of-nursing%2Fdocuments%2Fcouncil-documents%2Fprofessional-development%2Ffellowship-roll-of-honour.pdf&index_url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.rcn.org.uk%2F-%2Fmedia%2Froyal-college-of-nursing%2Fdocuments%2Fcouncil-documents%2Fprofessional-development%2Ffellowship-roll-of-honour.pdf&auth=M1Tbp8h%2FCwu%2BVMfa0sJVMQ&search_referer=http%3A%2F%2Fwww2.rcn.org.uk%2F&query=roll%20of%20honour&profile=_default&identifier=1468232596.29709|publisher=Royal College of Nursing|accessdate=11 July 2016}}</ref> She died on 18 June 1992.<ref>{{cite news|title=In the estate of Kofoworola Abeni Pratt deceased|url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/newspaperRetrieve.do?sgHitCountType=None&sort=DateAscend&tabID=T003&prodId=TTDA&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchId=R1&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=1&qrySerId=Locale%28en%2C%2C%29%3AFQE%3D%28tx%2CNone%2C22%29Kofoworola+Abeni+Pratt%24&retrieveFormat=MULTIPAGE_DOCUMENT&userGroupName=lancs&inPS=true&contentSet=LTO&&docId=&docLevel=FASCIMILE&workId=&relevancePageBatch=IF501975871&contentSet=TDA&callistoContentSet=TDA&docPage=article&hilite=y|accessdate=11 July 2016|work=The Times|date=24 April 1993|page=16|subscription=yes}}</ref>
